The value of `count` is neither incrementing or decrementing inside the method. The variable is assigned to the value of `i` in the first line of your method. It stays at that value **for that specific method invocation**. This means when you call `sayHi(4)` you are executing the following pseudo code:

    public static void sayHi(4) {
        int count = 4;
        System.out.println(4);
        if(4 == 0) return; // which is &quot;false&quot;


        System.out.println(&quot;hi!&quot;);
        sayHi(3); // 4 - 1

        System.out.println(4);

        System.out.println(&quot;Hello.&quot;);

    }

So at the start and at the end, the value `4` is printed, as you have such two `println()` statements (and you don&#39;t exit the method early at the `if()` statement). Due to the recursion, at some point you are calling `sayHi(0)`, which result in the following pseudo code execution:

    public static void sayHi(0) {
        int count = 0;
        System.out.println(0);
        if(0 == 0) return; // which is &quot;true&quot;


        System.out.println(&quot;hi!&quot;);
        sayHi(-1); // 0 - 1

        System.out.println(0);

        System.out.println(&quot;Hello.&quot;);
    }

There are two `println(0);` calls, but since the `if()` condition is met, this method exits at that location early and the second `println()` statement isn&#39;t executed at all. That&#39;s why you have only one `0` printed in your output.

